Title: 30 - Husband and Wife
  Chapter: 30-1 - Marriage
    Section: 30-1-1 - Incestuous marriages void.
      Enacted: Amended by Chapter by Chapter 217, 2022GS
      30-1-1(1): The following marriages are incestuous and void from the beginning, regardless of whether the relationship is legally recognized:
          30-1-1(1)(a): marriages between parents and children;
          30-1-1(1)(b): marriages between ancestors and descendants of every degree;
          30-1-1(1)(c): marriages between siblings of the half as well as the whole blood;
          30-1-1(1)(d): marriages between:
              30-1-1(1)(d)(i): uncles and nieces or nephews; or
              30-1-1(1)(d)(ii): aunts and nieces or nephews;
          30-1-1(1)(e): marriages between first cousins, except as provided in Subsection 2[Ref: 30-1-1(2)]
          30-1-1(1)(f): marriages between any individuals related to each other within and not including the fifth degree of consanguinity computed according to the rules of the civil law, except as provided in Subsection 2[Ref: 30-1-1(2)]
      30-1-1(2): First cousins may marry under the following circumstances:
          30-1-1(2)(a): both parties are 65 years of age or older; or
          30-1-1(2)(b): if both parties are 55 years of age or older, upon a finding by the district court, located in the district in which either party resides, that either party is unable to reproduce.
    Section: 30-1-2 - Marriages prohibited and void.
      Enacted: Amended by Chapter by Chapter 300, 2019GS
      30-1-2(1): The following marriages are prohibited and declared void:
          30-1-2(1)(a): when there is a spouse living, from whom the individual marrying has not been divorced;
          30-1-2(1)(b): except as provided in Subsection 2[Ref: 30-1-2(2)]
          30-1-2(1)(c): between a divorced individual and any individual other than the one from whom the divorce was secured until the divorce decree becomes absolute, and, if an appeal is taken, until after the affirmance of the decree.
      30-1-2(2): A marriage of an individual under 18 years old is not void if the individual:
          30-1-2(2)(a): is 16 or 17 years old and obtains consent from a parent or guardian and juvenile court authorization in accordance with Section 30-1-9[Ref: 30-1-9]
          30-1-2(2)(b): lawfully marries before May 14, 2019.
