    Section: 30-1-4.1 - Marriage recognition policy.
      Enacted: Enacted by Chapter by Chapter 261, 2004GS
      30-1-4.1(1): 
          30-1-4.1(1)(a): It is the policy of this state to recognize as marriage only the legal union of a man and a woman as provided in this chapter.
          30-1-4.1(1)(b): Except for the relationship of marriage between a man and a woman recognized pursuant to this chapter, this state will not recognize, enforce, or give legal effect to any law creating any legal status, rights, benefits, or duties that are substantially equivalent to those provided under Utah law to a man and a woman because they are married.
      30-1-4.1(2): Nothing in Subsection 1[Ref: 30-1-4.1(1)]
    Section: 30-1-4.5 - Validity of marriage not solemnized.
      Enacted: Amended by Chapter by Chapter 186, 2021GS
      30-1-4.5(1): A marriage which is not solemnized according to this chapter shall be legal and valid if a court or administrative order establishes that the marriage arises out of a contract between a man and a woman who:
          30-1-4.5(1)(a): are of legal age and capable of giving consent;
          30-1-4.5(1)(b): are legally capable of entering a solemnized marriage under the provisions of this chapter;
          30-1-4.5(1)(c): have cohabited;
          30-1-4.5(1)(d): mutually assume marital rights, duties, and obligations; and
          30-1-4.5(1)(e): who hold themselves out as and have acquired a uniform and general reputation as husband and wife.
      30-1-4.5(2): 
          30-1-4.5(2)(a): A petition for an unsolemnized marriage shall be filed during the relationship described in Subsection 1[Ref: 30-1-4.5(1)]
          30-1-4.5(2)(b): Evidence of a marriage recognizable under this section may be manifested in any form, and may be proved under the same general rules of evidence as facts in other cases.
    Section: 30-1-5 - Marriage solemnization -- Before unauthorized person -- Validity.
      Enacted: Amended by Chapter by Chapter 297, 2011GS
      30-1-5(1): A marriage solemnized before a person professing to have authority to perform marriages may not be invalidated for lack of authority, if consummated in the belief of the parties or either of them that the person had authority and that they have been lawfully married.
      30-1-5(2): This section may not be construed to validate a marriage that is prohibited or void under Section 30-1-2[Ref: 30-1-2]
