    Section: 30-1-7 - Marriage licenses -- Use within state -- Expiration.
      Enacted: Amended by Chapter by Chapter 305, 2021GS
      30-1-7(1): No marriage may be solemnized in this state without a license issued by the county clerk of any county of this state.
      30-1-7(2): A license issued within this state by a county clerk may only be used within this state.
      30-1-7(3): A license that is not used within 32 days after the day on which the licensed is issued is void.
    Section: 30-1-8 - Application for license -- Contents.
      Enacted: Amended by Chapter by Chapter 305, 2021GS
      30-1-8(1): As used in this section, "minor" means the same as that term is defined in Section 30-1-9[Ref: 30-1-9]
      30-1-8(2): A county clerk may issue a marriage license only after an application is filed with the county clerk's office, requiring the following information:
          30-1-8(2)(a): the full names of the applicants, including the maiden or bachelor name of each applicant;
          30-1-8(2)(b): the social security numbers of the applicants, unless an applicant has not been assigned a number;
          30-1-8(2)(c): the current address of each applicant;
          30-1-8(2)(d): the date and place of birth, including the town or city, county, state or country, if possible;
          30-1-8(2)(e): the names of the applicants' respective parents, including the maiden name of a mother; and
          30-1-8(2)(f): the birthplaces of the applicants' respective parents, including the town or city, county, state or country, if possible.
      30-1-8(3): 
          30-1-8(3)(a): If one or both of the applicants is a minor, the clerk shall provide each minor with a standard petition on a form provided by the Judicial Council to be presented to the juvenile court to obtain the authorization required by Section 30-1-9[Ref: 30-1-9]
          30-1-8(3)(b): The form described in Subsection a[Ref: 30-1-8(3)(a)]
              30-1-8(3)(b)(i): all information described in Subsection 2[Ref: 30-1-8(2)]
              30-1-8(3)(b)(ii): in accordance with Subsection 30-1-9(2)(a)[Ref: 30-1-9(2)(a)]
              30-1-8(3)(b)(iii): an affidavit for the parent or legal guardian to acknowledge the penalty described in Section 30-1-9.1[Ref: 30-1-9.1]
              30-1-8(3)(b)(iv): an affidavit for each applicant regarding the accuracy of the information contained in the marriage application signed under penalty of perjury; and
              30-1-8(3)(b)(v): a place for the clerk to sign that indicates that the following have provided documentation to support the information contained in the form:
                  30-1-8(3)(b)(v)(A): each applicant; and
                  30-1-8(3)(b)(v)(B): the minor's parent or legal guardian.
      30-1-8(4): 
          30-1-8(4)(a): The social security numbers obtained under the authority of this section may not be recorded on the marriage license, and are not open to inspection as a part of the vital statistics files.
          30-1-8(4)(b): The Department of Health, Bureau of Vital Records and Health Statistics shall, upon request, supply the social security numbers to the Office of Recovery Services within the Department of Human Services.
          30-1-8(4)(c): The Office of Recovery Services may not use a social security number obtained under the authority of this section for any reason other than the administration of child support services.
    Section: 30-1-9 - Marriage by minors -- Consent of parent or guardian -- Juvenile court authorization.
      Enacted: Amended by Chapter by Chapter 305, 2021GS
      30-1-9(1): For purposes of this section, "minor" means an individual that is 16 or 17 years old.
      30-1-9(2): 
          30-1-9(2)(a): If at the time of applying for a license the applicant is a minor, and not before the minor is married, a license may not be issued without the signed consent of the minor's parent or legal guardian given in person to the clerk, except that:
              30-1-9(2)(a)(i): if the parents of the minor are divorced, consent shall be given by the parent having legal custody of the minor as evidenced by an oath of affirmation to the clerk;
              30-1-9(2)(a)(ii): if the parents of the minor are divorced and have been awarded joint custody of the minor, consent shall be given by the parent having physical custody of the minor the majority of the time as evidenced by an oath of affirmation to the clerk; or
              30-1-9(2)(a)(iii): if the minor is not in the custody of a parent, the legal guardian shall provide the consent and provide proof of guardianship by court order as well as an oath of affirmation.
          30-1-9(2)(b): Each applicant and if an applicant is a minor, the minor's consenting parent or legal guardian, shall appear in person before the clerk and provide legal documentation to establish the following information:
              30-1-9(2)(b)(i): the legal relationship between the minor and the minor's parent or legal guardian;
              30-1-9(2)(b)(ii): the legal name and identity of the minor; and
              30-1-9(2)(b)(iii): the birth date of each applicant.
          30-1-9(2)(c): An individual may present the following documents to satisfy a requirement described in Subsection b[Ref: 30-1-9(2)(b)]
              30-1-9(2)(c)(i): for verifying the legal relationship between the minor and the minor's parent or legal guardian, one of the following:
                  30-1-9(2)(c)(i)(A): the minor's certified birth certificate with the name of the parent, and an official translation if the birth certificate is in a language other than English;
                  30-1-9(2)(c)(i)(B): a report of a birth abroad with the name of the minor and the parent;
                  30-1-9(2)(c)(i)(C): a certified adoption decree with the name of the minor and the parent; or
                  30-1-9(2)(c)(i)(D): a certified court order establishing custody or guardianship between the minor and the parent or legal guardian;
              30-1-9(2)(c)(ii): for verifying the legal name and identity of the minor, one of the following:
                  30-1-9(2)(c)(ii)(A): an expired or current passport;
                  30-1-9(2)(c)(ii)(B): a driver's license;
                  30-1-9(2)(c)(ii)(C): a certificate of naturalization;
                  30-1-9(2)(c)(ii)(D): a military identification; or
                  30-1-9(2)(c)(ii)(E): a government employee identification card from a federal, state, or municipal government; and
              30-1-9(2)(c)(iii): for verifying the birth date of each applicant, one of the following for each applicant:
                  30-1-9(2)(c)(iii)(A): a certified birth certificate;
                  30-1-9(2)(c)(iii)(B): a report of a birth abroad;
                  30-1-9(2)(c)(iii)(C): a certificate of naturalization;
                  30-1-9(2)(c)(iii)(D): a certificate of citizenship;
                  30-1-9(2)(c)(iii)(E): a passport;
                  30-1-9(2)(c)(iii)(F): a driver's license; or
                  30-1-9(2)(c)(iii)(G): a state identification card.
          30-1-9(2)(d): An individual may not use a temporary or altered document to satisfy a requirement described in Subsection b[Ref: 30-1-9(2)(b)]
      30-1-9(3): 
          30-1-9(3)(a): The minor and the parent or legal guardian of the minor shall obtain a written authorization to marry from:
              30-1-9(3)(a)(i): a judge of the court exercising juvenile jurisdiction in the county where either party to the marriage resides; or
              30-1-9(3)(a)(ii): a court commissioner as permitted by rule of the Judicial Council.
          30-1-9(3)(b): Before issuing written authorization for a minor to marry, the judge or court commissioner shall determine:
              30-1-9(3)(b)(i): that the minor is entering into the marriage voluntarily; and
              30-1-9(3)(b)(ii): the marriage is in the best interests of the minor under the circumstances.
          30-1-9(3)(c): The judge or court commissioner shall require that both parties to the marriage complete premarital counseling, except the requirement for premarital counseling may be waived if premarital counseling is not reasonably available.
          30-1-9(3)(d): The judge or court commissioner may require:
              30-1-9(3)(d)(i): that the minor continue to attend school, unless excused under Section 53G-6-204[Ref: 53G-6-204]
              30-1-9(3)(d)(ii): any other conditions that the court deems reasonable under the circumstances.
          30-1-9(3)(e): The judge or court commissioner may not issue a written authorization to the minor if the age difference between both parties to the marriage is more than seven years.
      30-1-9(4): 
          30-1-9(4)(a): The determination required in Subsection 3[Ref: 30-1-9(3)]
          30-1-9(4)(b): Any inquiry conducted by the judge or commissioner may be conducted in chambers.
