    Section: 30-1-32 - Master plan for counseling.
      Enacted: Amended by Chapter by Chapter 297, 2011GS
      30-1-32(1): It shall be the function and duty of the premarital counseling board, after holding public hearings, to make, adopt, and certify to the county legislative body a master plan for premarital counseling of marriage license applicants within the purposes and objectives of this act.
      30-1-32(2): The master plan described in Subsection 1[Ref: 30-1-32(1)]
          30-1-32(2)(a): counseling procedures that:
              30-1-32(2)(a)(i): will make applicants aware of problem areas in their proposed marriage;
              30-1-32(2)(a)(ii): suggest ways of meeting problems; and
              30-1-32(2)(a)(iii): will induce reconsideration or postponement when:
                  30-1-32(2)(a)(iii)(A): the applicants are not sufficiently matured or are not financially capable of meeting the responsibilities of marriage; or
                  30-1-32(2)(a)(iii)(B): are marrying for reasons not conducive to a sound lasting marriage; and
          30-1-32(2)(b): standards for evaluating premarital counseling received by the applicants, prior to their application for a marriage license, which would justify issuance of certificate without further counseling being given or required.
      30-1-32(3): The board may, from time to time, amend or extend the plan described in Subsection 1[Ref: 30-1-32(1)]
      30-1-32(4): The premarital counseling board may, subject to Subsection 5[Ref: 30-1-32(5)]
          30-1-32(4)(a): appoint a staff and employees as may be necessary for its work; and
          30-1-32(4)(b): contract with social service agencies or other consultants within the county or counties for services it requires.
      30-1-32(5): Expenditures for the appointments and contracts described in Subsection 4[Ref: 30-1-32(4)]
    Section: 30-1-33 - Conformity to master plan for counseling as prerequisite to marriage license -- Exceptions.
      Enacted: Amended by Chapter by Chapter 297, 2011GS
      30-1-33(1): Any person who applies for a marriage license shall have the right to secure the license and to marry notwithstanding their failure to conform to the required premarital counseling or their failure to obtain a certificate of authorization from the premarital counseling board if they wait six months from the date of application for issuance of the license.
      30-1-33(2): This chapter does not apply to any application for a marriage license where both parties are at least 19 years of age and neither has been previously divorced.
      30-1-33(3): This chapter does not apply to any application for a marriage license unless both applicants have physically resided in Utah for 60 days immediately preceding their application.
      30-1-33(4): Premarital counseling required by this act shall be considered fulfilled if the applicants present a certificate verified by a clergyman that the applicants have completed a course of premarital counseling approved by a church and given by or under the supervision of the clergyman.
    Section: 30-1-34 - Completion of counseling or education.
      Enacted: Amended by Chapter by Chapter 91, 2021GS
      30-1-34(1): The county clerk of a county that operates an online marriage application system and issues a marriage license to applicants who certify completion of premarital counseling or education in accordance with Subsection 2[Ref: 30-1-34(2)]
      30-1-34(2): 
          30-1-34(2)(a): To qualify for the reduced fee under Subsection 1[Ref: 30-1-34(1)] 2[Ref: 30-1-34(2)]
          30-1-34(2)(b): To complete premarital counseling or education, the applicants:
              30-1-34(2)(b)(i): shall obtain the premarital counseling or education from:
                  30-1-34(2)(b)(i)(A): a licensed or ordained minister or the minister's designee who is trained by the minister or denomination to conduct premarital counseling or education;
                  30-1-34(2)(b)(i)(B): an individual licensed under 58-60[Ref: 58-60]
                  30-1-34(2)(b)(i)(C): an individual certified by a national organization recognized by the Utah Marriage Commission, created in 63M-15[Ref: 63M-15]
                  30-1-34(2)(b)(i)(D): a family and consumer sciences educator;
