    Section: 30-2-11 - Action for consortium due to personal injury.
      Enacted: Amended by Chapter by Chapter 3, 2008GS
      30-2-11(1): For purposes of this section:
          30-2-11(1)(a): "injury" or "injured" means a significant permanent injury to a person that substantially changes that person's lifestyle and includes the following:
              30-2-11(1)(a)(i): a partial or complete paralysis of one or more of the extremities;
              30-2-11(1)(a)(ii): significant disfigurement; or
              30-2-11(1)(a)(iii): incapability of the person of performing the types of jobs the person performed before the injury; and
          30-2-11(1)(b): "spouse" means the legal relationship:
              30-2-11(1)(b)(i): established between a man and a woman as recognized by the laws of this state; and
              30-2-11(1)(b)(ii): existing at the time of the person's injury.
      30-2-11(2): The spouse of a person injured by a third party on or after May 4, 1997, may maintain an action against the third party to recover for loss of consortium.
      30-2-11(3): A claim for loss of consortium begins on the date of injury to the spouse.  The statute of limitations applicable to the injured person shall also apply to the spouse's claim of loss of consortium.
      30-2-11(4): A claim for the spouse's loss of consortium shall be:
          30-2-11(4)(a): made at the time the claim of the injured person is made and joinder of actions shall be compulsory; and
          30-2-11(4)(b): subject to the same defenses, limitations, immunities, and provisions applicable to the claims of the injured person.
      30-2-11(5): The spouse's action for loss of consortium:
          30-2-11(5)(a): shall be derivative from the cause of action existing in behalf of the injured person; and
          30-2-11(5)(b): may not exist in cases where the injured person would not have a cause of action.
      30-2-11(6): Fault of the spouse of the injured person, as well as fault of the injured person, shall be compared with the fault of all other parties, pursuant to Sections 78B-5-817[Ref: 78B-5-817] 78B-5-823[Ref: 78B-5-823]
      30-2-11(7): Damages awarded for loss of consortium, when combined with any award to the injured person for general damages, may not exceed any applicable statutory limit on noneconomic damages, including Section 78B-3-410[Ref: 78B-3-410]
      30-2-11(8): Damages awarded for loss of consortium which a governmental entity is required to pay, when combined with any award to the injured person which a governmental entity is required to pay, may not exceed the liability limit for one person in any one occurrence under 63G-7[Ref: 63G-7]
  Chapter: 30-3 - Divorce
    Section: 30-3-1 - Procedure -- Residence -- Grounds.
      Enacted: Amended by Chapter by Chapter 47, 1997GS
      30-3-1(1): Proceedings in divorce are commenced and conducted as provided by law for proceedings in civil causes, except as provided in this chapter.
      30-3-1(2): The court may decree a dissolution of the marriage contract between the petitioner and respondent on the grounds specified in Subsection 3[Ref: 30-3-1(3)]
      30-3-1(3): Grounds for divorce:
          30-3-1(3)(a): impotency of the respondent at the time of marriage;
          30-3-1(3)(b): adultery committed by the respondent subsequent to marriage;
          30-3-1(3)(c): willful desertion of the petitioner by the respondent for more than one year;
          30-3-1(3)(d): willful neglect of the respondent to provide for the petitioner the common necessaries of life;
          30-3-1(3)(e): habitual drunkenness of the respondent;
          30-3-1(3)(f): conviction of the respondent for a felony;
          30-3-1(3)(g): cruel treatment of the petitioner by the respondent to the extent of causing bodily injury or great mental distress to the petitioner;
          30-3-1(3)(h): irreconcilable differences of the marriage;
          30-3-1(3)(i): incurable insanity; or
          30-3-1(3)(j): when the husband and wife have lived separately under a decree of separate maintenance of any state for three consecutive years without cohabitation.
      30-3-1(4): A decree of divorce granted under Subsection j[Ref: 30-3-1(3)(j)]
      30-3-1(5): 
          30-3-1(5)(a): A divorce may not be granted on the grounds of insanity unless:
              30-3-1(5)(a)(i): the respondent has been adjudged insane by the appropriate authorities of this or another state prior to the commencement of the action; and
              30-3-1(5)(a)(ii): the court finds by the testimony of competent witnesses that the insanity of the respondent is incurable.
          30-3-1(5)(b): The court shall appoint for the respondent a guardian ad litem who shall protect the interests of the respondent.  A copy of the summons and complaint shall be served on the respondent in person or by publication, as provided by the laws of this state in other actions for divorce, or upon his guardian ad litem, and upon the county attorney for the county where the action is prosecuted.
          30-3-1(5)(c): The county attorney shall investigate the merits of the case and if the respondent resides out of this state, take depositions as necessary, attend the proceedings, and make a defense as is just to protect the rights of the respondent and the interests of the state.
          30-3-1(5)(d): In all actions the court and judge have jurisdiction over the payment of alimony, the distribution of property, and the custody and maintenance of minor children, as the courts and judges possess in other actions for divorce.
          30-3-1(5)(e): The petitioner or respondent may, if the respondent resides in this state, upon notice, have the respondent brought into the court at trial, or have an examination of the respondent by two or more competent physicians, to determine the mental condition of the respondent.  For this purpose either party may have leave from the court to enter any asylum or institution where the respondent may be confined.  The costs of court in this action shall be apportioned by the court.
    Section: 30-3-2 - Right of husband to divorce.
