    Section: 30-3-10 - Custody of a child -- Custody factors.
      Enacted: Amended by Chapter by Chapter 44, 2023GS
      30-3-10(1): If a married couple having one or more minor children are separated, or the married couple's marriage is declared void or dissolved, the court shall enter, and has continuing jurisdiction to modify, an order of custody and parent-time.
      30-3-10(2): In determining any form of custody and parent-time under Subsection 1[Ref: 30-3-10(1)]
          30-3-10(2)(a): evidence of domestic violence, neglect, physical abuse, sexual abuse, or emotional abuse, involving the child, the parent, or a household member of the parent;
          30-3-10(2)(b): the parent's demonstrated understanding of, responsiveness to, and ability to meet the developmental needs of the child, including the child's:
              30-3-10(2)(b)(i): physical needs;
              30-3-10(2)(b)(ii): emotional needs;
              30-3-10(2)(b)(iii): educational needs;
              30-3-10(2)(b)(iv): medical needs; and
              30-3-10(2)(b)(v): any special needs;
          30-3-10(2)(c): the parent's capacity and willingness to function as a parent, including:
              30-3-10(2)(c)(i): parenting skills;
              30-3-10(2)(c)(ii): co-parenting skills, including:
                  30-3-10(2)(c)(ii)(A): ability to appropriately communicate with the other parent;
                  30-3-10(2)(c)(ii)(B): ability to encourage the sharing of love and affection; and
                  30-3-10(2)(c)(ii)(C): willingness to allow frequent and continuous contact between the child and the other parent, except that, if the court determines that the parent is acting to protect the child from domestic violence, neglect, or abuse, the parent's protective actions may be taken into consideration; and
              30-3-10(2)(c)(iii): ability to provide personal care rather than surrogate care;
          30-3-10(2)(d): in accordance with Subsection 10[Ref: 30-3-10(10)]
          30-3-10(2)(e): the emotional stability of the parent;
          30-3-10(2)(f): the parent's inability to function as a parent because of drug abuse, excessive drinking, or other causes;
          30-3-10(2)(g): whether the parent has intentionally exposed the child to pornography or material harmful to minors, as "material" and "harmful to minors" are defined in Section 76-10-1201[Ref: 76-10-1201]
          30-3-10(2)(h): the parent's reasons for having relinquished custody or parent-time in the past;
          30-3-10(2)(i): duration and depth of desire for custody or parent-time;
          30-3-10(2)(j): the parent's religious compatibility with the child;
          30-3-10(2)(k): the parent's financial responsibility;
          30-3-10(2)(l): the child's interaction and relationship with step-parents, extended family members of other individuals who may significantly affect the child's best interests;
          30-3-10(2)(m): who has been the primary caretaker of the child;
          30-3-10(2)(n): previous parenting arrangements in which the child has been happy and well-adjusted in the home, school, and community;
          30-3-10(2)(o): the relative benefit of keeping siblings together;
          30-3-10(2)(p): the stated wishes and concerns of the child, taking into consideration the child's cognitive ability and emotional maturity;
          30-3-10(2)(q): the relative strength of the child's bond with the parent, meaning the depth, quality, and nature of the relationship between the parent and the child; and
          30-3-10(2)(r): any other factor the court finds relevant.
      30-3-10(3): There is a rebuttable presumption that joint legal custody, as defined in Section 30-3-10.1[Ref: 30-3-10.1]
          30-3-10(3)(a): evidence of domestic violence, neglect, physical abuse, sexual abuse, or emotional abuse involving the child, a parent, or a household member of the parent;
          30-3-10(3)(b): special physical or mental needs of a parent or child, making joint legal custody unreasonable;
          30-3-10(3)(c): physical distance between the residences of the parents, making joint decision making impractical in certain circumstances; or
          30-3-10(3)(d): any other factor the court considers relevant including those listed in this section and Section 30-3-10.2[Ref: 30-3-10.2]
      30-3-10(4): 
          30-3-10(4)(a): The person who desires joint legal custody shall file a proposed parenting plan in accordance with Sections 30-3-10.8[Ref: 30-3-10.8] 30-3-10.9[Ref: 30-3-10.9]
          30-3-10(4)(b): A presumption for joint legal custody may be rebutted by a showing by a preponderance of the evidence that it is not in the best interest of the child.
      30-3-10(5): 
          30-3-10(5)(a): A child may not be required by either party to testify unless the trier of fact determines that extenuating circumstances exist that would necessitate the testimony of the child be heard and there is no other reasonable method to present the child's testimony.
          30-3-10(5)(b): 
              30-3-10(5)(b)(i): The court may inquire of the child's and take into consideration the child's desires regarding future custody or parent-time schedules, but the expressed desires are not controlling and the court may determine the child's custody or parent-time otherwise.
              30-3-10(5)(b)(ii): The desires of a child 14 years old or older shall be given added weight, but is not the single controlling factor.
          30-3-10(5)(c): 
              30-3-10(5)(c)(i): If an interview with a child is conducted by the court pursuant to Subsection b[Ref: 30-3-10(5)(b)]
              30-3-10(5)(c)(ii): The prior consent of the parties may be obtained but is not necessary if the court finds that an interview with a child is the only method to ascertain the child's desires regarding custody.
      30-3-10(6): 
          30-3-10(6)(a): Except as provided in Subsection b[Ref: 30-3-10(6)(b)] 57-21-2[Ref: 57-21-2]
          30-3-10(6)(b): The court may not consider the disability of a parent as a factor in awarding custody or modifying an award of custody based on a determination of a substantial change in circumstances, unless the court makes specific findings that:
              30-3-10(6)(b)(i): the disability significantly or substantially inhibits the parent's ability to provide for the physical and emotional needs of the child at issue; and
              30-3-10(6)(b)(ii): the parent with a disability lacks sufficient human, monetary, or other resources available to supplement the parent's ability to provide for the physical and emotional needs of the child at issue.
          30-3-10(6)(c): Nothing in this section may be construed to apply to adoption proceedings under 78B-6-1[Ref: 78B-6-1]
      30-3-10(7): This section does not establish a preference for either parent solely because of the gender of the parent.
      30-3-10(8): This section establishes neither a preference nor a presumption for or against joint physical custody or sole physical custody, but allows the court and the family the widest discretion to choose a parenting plan that is in the best interest of the child.
      30-3-10(9): When an issue before the court involves custodial responsibility in the event of a deployment of one or both parents who are service members and the service member has not yet been notified of deployment, the court shall resolve the issue based on the standards in Sections 78B-20-306[Ref: 78B-20-306] 78B-20-309[Ref: 78B-20-309]
      30-3-10(10): In considering the past conduct and demonstrated moral standards of each party under Subsection d[Ref: 30-3-10(2)(d)]
          30-3-10(10)(a): consider or treat a parent's lawful possession or use of cannabis in a medicinal dosage form, a cannabis product in a medicinal dosage form, or a medical cannabis device, in accordance with 4-41a[Ref: 4-41a] 26B-4-2[Ref: 26B-4-2] 58-37-3.7(2)[Ref: 58-37-3.7(2)] 58-37-3.7(3)[Ref: 58-37-3.7(3)]
          30-3-10(10)(b): discriminate against a parent because of the parent's status as a:
              30-3-10(10)(b)(i): cannabis production establishment agent, as that term is defined in Section 4-41a-102[Ref: 4-41a-102]
              30-3-10(10)(b)(ii): medical cannabis pharmacy agent, as that term is defined in Section 26B-4-201[Ref: 26B-4-201]
              30-3-10(10)(b)(iii): medical cannabis courier agent, as that term is defined in Section 26B-4-201[Ref: 26B-4-201]
              30-3-10(10)(b)(iv): medical cannabis cardholder in accordance with 26B-4-2[Ref: 26B-4-2]
    Section: 30-3-10.1 - Definitions -- Joint legal custody -- Joint physical custody.
      Enacted: Amended by Chapter by Chapter 44, 2023GS
      30-3-10.1(1): 
          30-3-10.1(1)(a): "Custodial responsibility" includes all powers and duties relating to caretaking authority and decision-making authority for a child.
          30-3-10.1(1)(b): "Custodial responsibility" includes physical custody, legal custody, parenting time, right to access, visitation, and authority to grant limited contact with a child.
      30-3-10.1(2): "Joint legal custody":
          30-3-10.1(2)(a): means the sharing of the rights, privileges, duties, and powers of a parent by both parents, where specified;
          30-3-10.1(2)(b): may include an award of exclusive authority by the court to one parent to make specific decisions;
          30-3-10.1(2)(c): does not affect the physical custody of the child except as specified in the order of joint legal custody;
          30-3-10.1(2)(d): is not based on awarding equal or nearly equal periods of physical custody of and access to the child to each of the parents, as the best interest of the child often requires that a primary physical residence for the child be designated; and
          30-3-10.1(2)(e): does not prohibit the court from specifying one parent as the primary caretaker and one home as the primary residence of the child.
      30-3-10.1(3): "Joint physical custody":
          30-3-10.1(3)(a): means the child stays with each parent overnight for more than 30% of the year, and both parents contribute to the expenses of the child in addition to paying child support;
          30-3-10.1(3)(b): can mean equal or nearly equal periods of physical custody of and access to the child by each of the parents, as required to meet the best interest of the child;
          30-3-10.1(3)(c): may require that a primary physical residence for the child be designated; and
          30-3-10.1(3)(d): does not prohibit the court from specifying one parent as the primary caretaker and one home as the primary residence of the child.
      30-3-10.1(4): " Service member" means a member of a uniformed service.
      30-3-10.1(5): "Uniformed service" means:
          30-3-10.1(5)(a): active and reserve components of the United States Armed Forces;
          30-3-10.1(5)(b): the United States Merchant Marine;
          30-3-10.1(5)(c): the commissioned corps of the United States Public Health Service;
          30-3-10.1(5)(d): the commissioned corps of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration of the United States; or
          30-3-10.1(5)(e): the National Guard of a state.
    Section: 30-3-10.2 - Joint custody order -- Factors for court determination -- Public assistance.
      Enacted: Amended by Chapter by Chapter 188, 2019GS
      30-3-10.2(1): The court may order joint legal custody or joint physical custody or both if one or both parents have filed a parenting plan in accordance with Section 30-3-10.8[Ref: 30-3-10.8]
      30-3-10.2(2): In determining whether the best interest of a child will be served by ordering joint legal custody or joint physical custody or both, the court shall consider the custody factors in Section 30-3-10[Ref: 30-3-10]
          30-3-10.2(2)(a): whether the physical, psychological, and emotional needs and development of the child will benefit from joint legal custody or joint physical custody or both;
          30-3-10.2(2)(b): the ability of the parents to give first priority to the welfare of the child and reach shared decisions in the child's best interest;
          30-3-10.2(2)(c): co-parenting skills, including:
              30-3-10.2(2)(c)(i): ability to appropriately communicate with the other parent;
              30-3-10.2(2)(c)(ii): ability to encourage the sharing of love and affection; and
              30-3-10.2(2)(c)(iii): willingness to allow frequent and continuous contact between the child and the other parent, except that, if the court determines that the parent is acting to protect the child from domestic violence, neglect, or abuse, the parent's protective actions may be taken into consideration; and
          30-3-10.2(2)(d): whether both parents participated in raising the child before the divorce;
          30-3-10.2(2)(e): the geographical proximity of the homes of the parents;
          30-3-10.2(2)(f): the preference of the child if the child is of sufficient age and capacity to reason so as to form an intelligent preference as to joint legal custody or joint physical custody or both;
          30-3-10.2(2)(g): the maturity of the parents and their willingness and ability to protect the child from conflict that may arise between the parents;
          30-3-10.2(2)(h): the past and present ability of the parents to cooperate with each other and make decisions jointly; and
          30-3-10.2(2)(i): any other factor the court finds relevant.
      30-3-10.2(3): The determination of the best interest of the child shall be by a preponderance of the evidence.
      30-3-10.2(4): The court shall inform both parties that an order for joint physical custody may preclude eligibility for cash assistance provided under 35A-3[Ref: 35A-3]
      30-3-10.2(5): The court may order that when possible the parties attempt to settle future disputes by a dispute resolution method before seeking enforcement or modification of the terms and conditions of the order of joint legal custody or joint physical custody through litigation, except in emergency situations requiring ex parte orders to protect the child.
    Section: 30-3-10.3 - Terms of joint legal or physical custody order.
      Enacted: Amended by Chapter by Chapter 271, 2012GS
      30-3-10.3(1): Unless the court orders otherwise, before a final order of joint legal custody or joint physical custody is entered both parties shall attend the mandatory course for divorcing parents, as provided in Section 30-3-11.3[Ref: 30-3-11.3]
      30-3-10.3(2): An order of joint legal or physical custody shall provide terms the court determines appropriate, which may include specifying:
          30-3-10.3(2)(a): either the county of residence of the child, until altered by further order of the court, or the custodian who has the sole legal right to determine the residence of the child;
          30-3-10.3(2)(b): that the parents shall exchange information concerning the health, education, and welfare of the child, and where possible, confer before making decisions concerning any of these areas;
          30-3-10.3(2)(c): the rights and duties of each parent regarding the child's present and future physical care, support, and education;
          30-3-10.3(2)(d): provisions to minimize disruption of the child's attendance at school and other activities, his daily routine, and his association with friends; and
          30-3-10.3(2)(e): as necessary, the remaining parental rights, privileges, duties, and powers to be exercised by the parents solely, concurrently, or jointly.
      30-3-10.3(3): The court shall, where possible, include in the order the terms of the parenting plan provided in accordance with Section 30-3-10.8[Ref: 30-3-10.8]
      30-3-10.3(4): Any parental rights not specifically addressed by the court order may be exercised by the parent having physical custody of the child the majority of the time.
      30-3-10.3(5): The appointment of joint legal or physical custodians does not impair or limit the authority of the court to order support of the child, including payments by one custodian to the other.
      30-3-10.3(6): An order of joint legal custody, in itself, is not grounds for modifying a support order.
      30-3-10.3(7): An order of joint legal or physical custody shall require a parenting plan incorporating a dispute resolution procedure the parties agree to use:
          30-3-10.3(7)(a): in accordance with Section 30-3-10.9[Ref: 30-3-10.9] 30-3-10.2(5)[Ref: 30-3-10.2(5)]
          30-3-10.3(7)(b): before seeking enforcement or modification of the terms and conditions of the order of joint legal or physical custody through litigation, except in emergency situations requiring ex parte orders to protect the child.
    Section: 30-3-10.4 - Modification or termination of order.
      Enacted: Amended by Chapter by Chapter 44, 2023GS
      30-3-10.4(1): On the petition of one or both of the parents, or the joint legal or physical custodians if they are not the parents, the court may, after a hearing, modify or terminate an order that established joint legal custody or joint physical custody if:
          30-3-10.4(1)(a): the verified petition or accompanying affidavit initially alleges that admissible evidence will show that the circumstances of the child or one or both parents or joint legal or physical custodians have materially and substantially changed since the entry of the order to be modified;
          30-3-10.4(1)(b): a modification of the terms and conditions of the order would be an improvement for and in the best interest of the child; and
          30-3-10.4(1)(c): 
              30-3-10.4(1)(c)(i): both parents have complied in good faith with the dispute resolution procedure in accordance with Subsection 30-3-10.3(7)[Ref: 30-3-10.3(7)]
              30-3-10.4(1)(c)(ii): if no dispute resolution procedure is contained in the order that established joint legal custody or joint physical custody, the court orders the parents to participate in a dispute resolution procedure in accordance with Subsection 30-3-10.2(5)[Ref: 30-3-10.2(5)]
      30-3-10.4(2): 
          30-3-10.4(2)(a): In determining whether the best interest of a child will be served by either modifying or terminating the joint legal custody or joint physical custody order, the court shall, in addition to other factors the court considers relevant, consider the factors outlined in Section 30-3-10[Ref: 30-3-10] 30-3-10.2(2)[Ref: 30-3-10.2(2)]
          30-3-10.4(2)(b): A court order modifying or terminating an existing joint legal custody or joint physical custody order shall contain written findings that:
              30-3-10.4(2)(b)(i): a material and substantial change of circumstance has occurred; and
              30-3-10.4(2)(b)(ii): a modification of the terms and conditions of the order would be an improvement for and in the best interest of the child.
          30-3-10.4(2)(c): The court shall give substantial weight to the existing joint legal custody or joint physical custody order when the child is thriving, happy, and well-adjusted.
      30-3-10.4(3): The court shall, in every case regarding a petition for termination of a joint legal custody or joint physical custody order, consider reasonable alternatives to preserve the existing order in accordance with Subsection 30-3-10(3)[Ref: 30-3-10(3)] 30-3-10(8)[Ref: 30-3-10(8)]
      30-3-10.4(4): A parent requesting a modification from sole custody to joint legal custody or joint physical custody or both, or any other type of shared parenting arrangement, shall file and serve a proposed parenting plan with the petition to modify in accordance with Section 30-3-10.8[Ref: 30-3-10.8]
      30-3-10.4(5): If the court finds that an action under this section is filed or answered frivolously and in a manner designed to harass the other party, the court shall assess attorney fees as costs against the offending party.
      30-3-10.4(6): If an issue before the court involves custodial responsibility in the event of deployment of one or both parents who are service members, and the service member has not yet been notified of deployment, the court shall resolve the issue based on the standards in Sections 78B-20-306[Ref: 78B-20-306] 78B-20-309[Ref: 78B-20-309]
