    Section: 30-3-35.2 - Equal parent-time schedule.
      Enacted: Enacted by Chapter by Chapter 399, 2021GS
      30-3-35.2(1): 
          30-3-35.2(1)(a): A court may order the equal parent-time schedule described in this section if the court determines that:
              30-3-35.2(1)(a)(i): the equal parent-time schedule is in the child's best interest;
              30-3-35.2(1)(a)(ii): each parent has been actively involved in the child's life; and
              30-3-35.2(1)(a)(iii): each parent can effectively facilitate the equal parent-time schedule.
          30-3-35.2(1)(b): To determine whether each parent has been actively involved in the child's life, the court shall consider:
              30-3-35.2(1)(b)(i): each parent's demonstrated responsibility in caring for the child;
              30-3-35.2(1)(b)(ii): each parent's involvement in child care;
              30-3-35.2(1)(b)(iii): each parent's presence or volunteer efforts in the child's school and at extracurricular activities;
              30-3-35.2(1)(b)(iv): each parent's assistance with the child's homework;
              30-3-35.2(1)(b)(v): each parent's involvement in preparation of meals, bath time, and bedtime for the child;
              30-3-35.2(1)(b)(vi): each parent's bond with the child; and
              30-3-35.2(1)(b)(vii): any other factor the court considers relevant.
          30-3-35.2(1)(c): To determine whether each parent can effectively facilitate the equal parent-time schedule, the court shall consider:
              30-3-35.2(1)(c)(i): the geographic distance between the residence of each parent and the distance between each residence and the child's school;
              30-3-35.2(1)(c)(ii): each parent's ability to assist with the child's after school care;
              30-3-35.2(1)(c)(iii): the health of the child and each parent, consistent with Subsection 30-3-10(6)[Ref: 30-3-10(6)]
              30-3-35.2(1)(c)(iv): the flexibility of each parent's employment or other schedule;
              30-3-35.2(1)(c)(v): each parent's ability to provide appropriate playtime with the child;
              30-3-35.2(1)(c)(vi): each parent's history and ability to implement a flexible schedule for the child;
              30-3-35.2(1)(c)(vii): physical facilities of each parent's residence; and
              30-3-35.2(1)(c)(viii): any other factor the court considers relevant.
      30-3-35.2(2): 
          30-3-35.2(2)(a): If the parties agree to or the court orders the equal parent-time schedule described in this section, a parenting plan in accordance with Sections 30-3-10.7[Ref: 30-3-10.7] 30-3-10.10[Ref: 30-3-10.10]
          30-3-35.2(2)(b): An order under this section shall result in 182 overnights per year for one parent, and 183 overnights per year for the other parent.
          30-3-35.2(2)(c): Under the equal parent-time schedule, neither parent is considered to have the child the majority of the time for the purposes of Subsection 30-3-10.3(4)[Ref: 30-3-10.3(4)] 30-3-10.9(5)(c)(ii)[Ref: 30-3-10.9(5)(c)(ii)]
          30-3-35.2(2)(d): Child support for the equal parent-time schedule shall be consistent with Section 78B-12-208[Ref: 78B-12-208]
          30-3-35.2(2)(e): 
              30-3-35.2(2)(e)(i): A court shall determine which parent receives 182 overnights and which parent receives 183 overnights for parent-time.
              30-3-35.2(2)(e)(ii): For the purpose of calculating child support under Section 78B-12-208[Ref: 78B-12-208] Subsection i[Ref: 30-3-35.2(2)(e)(i)]
      30-3-35.2(3): 
          30-3-35.2(3)(a): Unless the parents agree otherwise and subject to a holiday, the equal parent-time schedule is as follows:
              30-3-35.2(3)(a)(i): one parent shall exercise parent-time starting Monday morning and ending  Wednesday morning;
              30-3-35.2(3)(a)(ii): the other parent shall exercise parent-time starting Wednesday morning and ending Friday morning; and
              30-3-35.2(3)(a)(iii): each parent shall alternate weeks exercising parent-time starting Friday morning and ending Monday morning.
          30-3-35.2(3)(b): The child exchange shall take place:
              30-3-35.2(3)(b)(i): at the time the child's school begins; or
              30-3-35.2(3)(b)(ii): if school is not in session, at 9 a.m.
      30-3-35.2(4): 
          30-3-35.2(4)(a): The parents may create a holiday schedule.
          30-3-35.2(4)(b): If the parents are unable to create a holiday schedule under Subsection a[Ref: 30-3-35.2(4)(a)]
              30-3-35.2(4)(b)(i): order the holiday schedule described in Section 30-3-35[Ref: 30-3-35]
              30-3-35.2(4)(b)(ii): designate which parent shall exercise parent-time for each holiday described in Section 30-3-35[Ref: 30-3-35]
      30-3-35.2(5): 
          30-3-35.2(5)(a): Each year, a parent may designate two consecutive weeks to exercise uninterrupted parent-time during the summer when school is not in session.
          30-3-35.2(5)(b): 
              30-3-35.2(5)(b)(i): One parent may make a designation at any time and the other parent may make a designation after May 1.
              30-3-35.2(5)(b)(ii): A parent shall make a designation at least 30 days before the day on which the designated two-week period begins.
          30-3-35.2(5)(c): The court shall designate which parent may make the earlier designation described in Subsection i[Ref: 30-3-35.2(5)(b)(i)]
          30-3-35.2(5)(d): The two consecutive weeks described in Subsection a[Ref: 30-3-35.2(5)(a)]
    Section: 30-3-35.5 - Minimum schedule for parent-time for child under five years old.
      Enacted: Amended by Chapter by Chapter 437, 2023GS
      30-3-35.5(1): As used in this section, "Juneteenth National Freedom Day" means the day on which the Juneteenth National Freedom Day holiday is celebrated in this state in accordance with Section 63G-1-301[Ref: 63G-1-301]
