      30-3-35.5(3): If the parties do not agree to a parent-time schedule, the schedules in Subsections 4[Ref: 30-3-35.5(4)] 9[Ref: 30-3-35.5(9)]
      30-3-35.5(4): For a child who is younger than five months old, the noncustodial parent is entitled to:
          30-3-35.5(4)(a): three two-hour visits every week; and
          30-3-35.5(4)(b): two hours for each holiday granted to the noncustodial parent in the holiday schedule under Subsection 16[Ref: 30-3-35.5(16)]
      30-3-35.5(5): For a child who is at least five months old but younger than nine months old, the noncustodial parent is entitled to:
          30-3-35.5(5)(a): three three-hour visits every week; and
          30-3-35.5(5)(b): two hours for each holiday granted to the noncustodial parent in the holiday schedule under Subsection 16[Ref: 30-3-35.5(16)]
      30-3-35.5(6): For a child who is at least nine months old but younger than 12 months old, the noncustodial parent is entitled to the child:
          30-3-35.5(6)(a): one eight-hour visit every week;
          30-3-35.5(6)(b): one three-hour visit every week; and
          30-3-35.5(6)(c): eight hours for each holiday granted to the noncustodial parent in accordance with the holiday schedule under Subsection 16[Ref: 30-3-35.5(16)]
      30-3-35.5(7): For a child who is at least 12 months old but younger than 18 months old, the noncustodial parent is entitled to:
          30-3-35.5(7)(a): one three-hour visit every week;
          30-3-35.5(7)(b): one eight-hour visit on alternating weekends to be specified by the noncustodial parent or court;
          30-3-35.5(7)(c): an overnight visit on opposite weekends from Subsection b[Ref: 30-3-35.5(7)(b)]
          30-3-35.5(7)(d): eight hours for each holiday granted to the noncustodial parent in the holiday schedule under Subsection 16[Ref: 30-3-35.5(16)]
      30-3-35.5(8): For a child who is at least 18 months old but younger than three years old, the noncustodial parent is entitled to:
          30-3-35.5(8)(a): one weekday evening to be specified by the noncustodial parent or the court:
              30-3-35.5(8)(a)(i): beginning at 5:30 p.m. and ending at 8:30 p.m.; or
              30-3-35.5(8)(a)(ii): if the child is being cared for during the day outside the child's regular place of residence and with advance notice to the custodial parent, beginning at the time that the child is picked up from the caregiver and ending at 8:30 p.m.;
          30-3-35.5(8)(b): beginning on the first weekend after the entry of the decree, alternating weekends beginning at 6 p.m. on Friday and ending at 7 p.m. on Sunday;
          30-3-35.5(8)(c): each holiday granted to the noncustodial parent in accordance with the holiday schedule described in Subsection 16[Ref: 30-3-35.5(16)]
          30-3-35.5(8)(d): extended parent-time for two one-week periods, separated by at least four weeks, at the option of the noncustodial parent, as follows:
              30-3-35.5(8)(d)(i): one week of uninterrupted parent-time for the noncustodial parent; and
              30-3-35.5(8)(d)(ii): one week of interrupted parent-time where the custodial parent may have an equal amount of weekday parent-time as the noncustodial parent on the same day on which the noncustodial parent is granted weekday parent-time under Subsection a[Ref: 30-3-35.5(8)(a)]
      30-3-35.5(9): For a child who is at least three years old but younger than five years old, the noncustodial parent is entitled to:
          30-3-35.5(9)(a): one weekday evening to be specified by the noncustodial parent or the court:
              30-3-35.5(9)(a)(i): beginning at 5:30 p.m. and ending at 8:30 p.m.; or
              30-3-35.5(9)(a)(ii): if the child is being cared for during the day outside the child's regular place of residence and with advance notice to the custodial parent, beginning at the time that the child is picked up from the caregiver and ending at 8:30 p.m.;
          30-3-35.5(9)(b): beginning on the first weekend after the entry of the decree, alternating weekends beginning at 6 p.m. on Friday and ending at 7 p.m. on Sunday;
          30-3-35.5(9)(c): each holiday granted to the noncustodial parent in accordance with the holiday schedule described in Subsection 16[Ref: 30-3-35.5(16)]
          30-3-35.5(9)(d): extended parent-time for two two-week periods, separated by at least four weeks, at the option of the noncustodial parent, as follows:
              30-3-35.5(9)(d)(i): two weeks of uninterrupted parent-time, which may be consecutive, for the noncustodial parent; and
              30-3-35.5(9)(d)(ii): two weeks of interrupted parent-time, which may be consecutive, where the custodial parent may have an equal amount of weekday parent-time as the noncustodial parent on the same day on which the noncustodial parent is granted weekday parent-time under Subsection a[Ref: 30-3-35.5(9)(a)]
      30-3-35.5(10): For a child who is at least 18 months old but younger than five years old, the custodial parent is entitled to one week of uninterrupted extended parent-time.
      30-3-35.5(11): 
          30-3-35.5(11)(a): For a child who is nine months old or older, the noncustodial parent shall have at least two times a week:
              30-3-35.5(11)(a)(i): brief telephone contact at reasonable hours and for a reasonable duration; and
              30-3-35.5(11)(a)(ii): virtual parent-time, if the equipment is reasonably available and the parents reside at least 100 miles apart, at reasonable hours and for reasonable duration.
          30-3-35.5(11)(b): If the parties cannot agree on whether the equipment is reasonably available, the court shall decide whether the equipment for virtual parent-time is reasonably available, taking into consideration:
              30-3-35.5(11)(b)(i): the best interests of the child;
              30-3-35.5(11)(b)(ii): each parent's ability to handle any additional expenses for virtual parent-time; and
              30-3-35.5(11)(b)(iii): any other factors the court considers material.
          30-3-35.5(11)(c): Virtual parent-time supplements, but does not replace, in-person parent-time.
      30-3-35.5(12): For a child who is younger than nine months old, unless the parents agree otherwise, parent-time should take place in the home of the custodial parent, an established child-care setting, or other environment familiar to the child.
      30-3-35.5(13): 
          30-3-35.5(13)(a): Changes may not be made to the parent-time schedule under this section, except that if a conflict arises in the parent-time schedule, the following order of precedence shall be applied when determining which parent is entitled to parent-time:
              30-3-35.5(13)(a)(i): the holiday schedule for Mother's Day or Father's Day under Subsection 16[Ref: 30-3-35.5(16)]
              30-3-35.5(13)(a)(ii): the holiday schedule for the child's birthday, unless a parent is exercising uninterrupted extended parent-time under Subsection d[Ref: 30-3-35.5(8)(d)] d[Ref: 30-3-35.5(9)(d)] 10[Ref: 30-3-35.5(10)]
              30-3-35.5(13)(a)(iii): the holiday schedule for any holiday under Subsection 16[Ref: 30-3-35.5(16)]
              30-3-35.5(13)(a)(iv): extended parent-time under Subsection d[Ref: 30-3-35.5(8)(d)] d[Ref: 30-3-35.5(9)(d)] 10[Ref: 30-3-35.5(10)]
              30-3-35.5(13)(a)(v): the schedule for weekday or weekend parent-time.
          30-3-35.5(13)(b): A parent exercising parent-time for the child's birthday may bring other siblings along for the child's birthday.
      30-3-35.5(14): If a holiday falls on a regularly scheduled school day, the parent exercising parent-time shall be responsible for the child's attendance at school for that school day.
      30-3-35.5(15): A parent shall notify the other parent at least 30 days in advance of the parent's plans for the exercise of extended parent-time under Subsection d[Ref: 30-3-35.5(8)(d)] d[Ref: 30-3-35.5(9)(d)] 10[Ref: 30-3-35.5(10)]
      30-3-35.5(16): The following table is the holiday schedule for parent-time under this section.
    Section: 30-3-36 - Special circumstances.
      Enacted: Amended by Chapter by Chapter 255, 2001GS
      30-3-36(1): When parent-time has not taken place for an extended period of time and the child lacks an appropriate bond with the noncustodial parent, both parents shall consider the possible adverse effects upon the child and gradually reintroduce an appropriate parent-time plan for the noncustodial parent.
      30-3-36(2): For emergency purposes, whenever the child travels with either parent, all of the following will be provided to the other parent:
          30-3-36(2)(a): an itinerary of travel dates;
          30-3-36(2)(b): destinations;
          30-3-36(2)(c): places where the child or traveling parent can be reached; and
          30-3-36(2)(d): the name and telephone number of an available third person who would be knowledgeable of the child's location.
      30-3-36(3): Unchaperoned travel of a child under the age of five years is not recommended.
    Section: 30-3-37 - Relocation.
      Enacted: Amended by Chapter by Chapter 354, 2020GS
      30-3-37(1): For purposes of this section, "relocation" means moving 150 miles or more from the residence of the other parent.
      30-3-37(2): The relocating parent shall provide 60 days advance written notice of the intended relocation to the other parent.  The written notice of relocation shall contain statements affirming the following:
          30-3-37(2)(a): the parent-time provisions in Subsection 6[Ref: 30-3-37(6)]
          30-3-37(2)(b): neither parent will interfere with the other's parental rights pursuant to court ordered parent-time arrangements, or the schedule approved by both parties.
      30-3-37(3): The court shall, upon motion of any party or upon the court's own motion, schedule a hearing with notice to review the notice of relocation and parent-time schedule as provided in Section 30-3-35[Ref: 30-3-35]
      30-3-37(4): In a hearing to review the notice of relocation, the court shall, in determining if the relocation of a custodial parent is in the best interest of the child, consider any other factors that the court considers relevant to the determination.  If the court determines that relocation is not in the best interest of the child, and the custodial parent relocates, the court may order a change of custody.
      30-3-37(5): If the court finds that the relocation is in the best interest of the child, the court shall determine the parent-time schedule and allocate the transportation costs that will be incurred for the child to visit the noncustodial parent.  In making its determination, court shall consider:
          30-3-37(5)(a): the reason for the parent's relocation;
          30-3-37(5)(b): the additional costs or difficulty to both parents in exercising parent-time;
          30-3-37(5)(c): the economic resources of both parents; and
          30-3-37(5)(d): other factors the court considers necessary and relevant.
      30-3-37(6): Unless otherwise ordered by the court, upon the relocation, as defined in Subsection 1[Ref: 30-3-37(1)]
          30-3-37(6)(a): in years ending in an odd number, the child shall spend the following holidays with the noncustodial parent:
              30-3-37(6)(a)(i): Thanksgiving holiday beginning Wednesday until Sunday; and
              30-3-37(6)(a)(ii): Spring break, if applicable, beginning the last day of school before the holiday until the day before school resumes;
          30-3-37(6)(b): in years ending in an even number, the child shall spend the following holidays with the noncustodial parent:
              30-3-37(6)(b)(i): the entire winter school break period; and
              30-3-37(6)(b)(ii): the Fall school break beginning the last day of school before the holiday until the day before school resumes;
          30-3-37(6)(c): extended parent-time equal to 1/2 of the summer or off-track time for consecutive weeks.  The children should be returned to the custodial home no later than seven days before school begins; however, this week shall be counted when determining the amount of parent-time to be divided between the parents for the summer or off-track period; and
          30-3-37(6)(d): one weekend per month, at the option and expense of the noncustodial parent.
      30-3-37(7): The court may also set a parent-time schedule for children under the age of five.  The schedule shall take into consideration the following:
          30-3-37(7)(a): the age of the child;
          30-3-37(7)(b): the developmental needs of the child;
          30-3-37(7)(c): the distance between the parents' homes;
          30-3-37(7)(d): the travel arrangements and cost;
          30-3-37(7)(e): the level of attachment between the child and the noncustodial parent; and
          30-3-37(7)(f): any other factors relevant to the best interest of the child.
      30-3-37(8): The noncustodial parent's monthly weekend entitlement is subject to the following restrictions.
          30-3-37(8)(a): If the noncustodial parent has not designated a specific weekend for parent-time, the noncustodial parent shall receive the last weekend of each month unless a holiday assigned to the custodial parent falls on that particular weekend.  If a holiday assigned to the custodial parent falls on the last weekend of the month, the noncustodial parent shall be entitled to the next to the last weekend of the month.
          30-3-37(8)(b): If a noncustodial parent's extended parent-time or parent-time over a holiday extends into or through the first weekend of the next month, that weekend shall be considered the noncustodial parent's monthly weekend entitlement for that month.
          30-3-37(8)(c): If a child is out of school for teacher development days or snow days after the children begin the school year, or other days not included in the list of holidays in Subsection 6[Ref: 30-3-37(6)]
      30-3-37(9): The custodial parent is entitled to all parent-time not specifically allocated to the noncustodial parent.
      30-3-37(10): In the event finances and distance preclude the exercise of minimum parent-time for the noncustodial parent during the school year, the court should consider awarding more time for the noncustodial parent during the summer time if it is in the best interests of the children.
      30-3-37(11): Upon the motion of any party, the court may order uninterrupted parent-time with the noncustodial parent for a minimum of 30 days during extended parent-time, unless the court finds it is not in the best interests of the child.  If the court orders uninterrupted parent-time during a period not covered by this section, it shall specify in its order which parent is responsible for the child's travel expenses.
      30-3-37(12): Unless otherwise ordered by the court the relocating party shall be responsible for all the child's travel expenses relating to Subsections a[Ref: 30-3-37(6)(a)] b[Ref: 30-3-37(6)(b)] c[Ref: 30-3-37(6)(c)] 6[Ref: 30-3-37(6)]
      30-3-37(13): The court may apply this provision to any preexisting decree of divorce.
      30-3-37(14): Any action under this section may be set for an expedited hearing.
      30-3-37(15): A parent who fails to comply with the notice of relocation in Subsection 2[Ref: 30-3-37(2)]
    Section: 30-3-38 - Expedited Parent-time Enforcement Program.
      Enacted: Amended by Chapter by Chapter 327, 2023GS
      30-3-38(1): There is established an Expedited Parent-time Enforcement Program in the third judicial district to be administered by the Administrative Office of the Courts.
      30-3-38(2): As used in this section:
          30-3-38(2)(a): "Mediator" means a person who:
              30-3-38(2)(a)(i): is qualified to mediate parent-time disputes under criteria established by the Administrative Office of the Courts; and
              30-3-38(2)(a)(ii): agrees to follow billing guidelines established by the Administrative Office of the Courts and this section.
          30-3-38(2)(b): "Services to facilitate parent-time" or "services" means services designed to assist families in resolving parent-time problems through:
              30-3-38(2)(b)(i): counseling;
              30-3-38(2)(b)(ii): supervised parent-time;
              30-3-38(2)(b)(iii): neutral drop-off and pick-up;
              30-3-38(2)(b)(iv): educational classes; and
              30-3-38(2)(b)(v): other related activities.
      30-3-38(3): 
          30-3-38(3)(a): If a parent files a motion in the third district court alleging that court-ordered parent-time rights are being violated, the clerk of the court, after assigning the case to a judge, shall refer the case to the administrator of this program for assignment to a mediator, unless a parent is incarcerated or otherwise unavailable.  Unless the court rules otherwise, a parent residing outside of the state is not unavailable.  The director of the program for the courts, the court, or the mediator may excuse either party from the requirement to mediate for good cause.
          30-3-38(3)(b): Upon receipt of a case, the mediator shall:
              30-3-38(3)(b)(i): meet with the parents to address parent-time issues within 15 days of the motion being filed;
              30-3-38(3)(b)(ii): assess the situation;
              30-3-38(3)(b)(iii): facilitate an agreement on parent-time between the parents; and
              30-3-38(3)(b)(iv): determine whether a referral to a service provider under Subsection c[Ref: 30-3-38(3)(c)]
          30-3-38(3)(c): While a case is in mediation, a mediator may refer the parents to a service provider designated by the Department of Health and Human Services for services to facilitate parent-time if:
              30-3-38(3)(c)(i): the services may be of significant benefit to the parents; or
              30-3-38(3)(c)(ii): 
                  30-3-38(3)(c)(ii)(A): a mediated agreement between the parents is unlikely; and
                  30-3-38(3)(c)(ii)(B): the services may facilitate an agreement.
          30-3-38(3)(d): At any time during mediation, a mediator shall terminate mediation and transfer the case to the administrator of the program for referral to the judge or court commissioner to whom the case was assigned under Subsection a[Ref: 30-3-38(3)(a)]
              30-3-38(3)(d)(i): a written agreement between the parents is reached; or
              30-3-38(3)(d)(ii): the parents are unable to reach an agreement through mediation and:
                  30-3-38(3)(d)(ii)(A): the parents have received services to facilitate parent-time;
                  30-3-38(3)(d)(ii)(B): both parents object to receiving services to facilitate parent-time; or
                  30-3-38(3)(d)(ii)(C): the parents are unlikely to benefit from receiving services to facilitate parent-time.
          30-3-38(3)(e): Upon receiving a case from the administrator of the program, a judge or court commissioner may:
              30-3-38(3)(e)(i): review the agreement of the parents and, if acceptable, sign it as an order;
              30-3-38(3)(e)(ii): order the parents to receive services to facilitate parent-time;
              30-3-38(3)(e)(iii): proceed with the case; or
              30-3-38(3)(e)(iv): take other appropriate action.
      30-3-38(4): 
          30-3-38(4)(a): If a parent makes a particularized allegation of physical or sexual abuse of a child who is the subject of a parent-time order against the other parent or a member of the other parent's household to a mediator or service provider, the mediator or service provider shall immediately report that information to:
              30-3-38(4)(a)(i): the judge assigned to the case who may immediately issue orders and take other appropriate action to resolve the allegation and protect the child; and
              30-3-38(4)(a)(ii): the Division of Child and Family Services within the Department of Health and Human Services in the manner required by 80-2-6[Ref: 80-2-6]
          30-3-38(4)(b): If an allegation under Subsection a[Ref: 30-3-38(4)(a)]
              30-3-38(4)(b)(i): the allegation has been resolved; or
              30-3-38(4)(b)(ii): a court orders otherwise.
          30-3-38(4)(c): Notwithstanding an allegation under Subsection a[Ref: 30-3-38(4)(a)]
      30-3-38(5): 
          30-3-38(5)(a): The Department of Health and Human Services may contract with one or more entities in accordance with 63G-6a[Ref: 63G-6a]
              30-3-38(5)(a)(i): services to facilitate parent-time;
              30-3-38(5)(a)(ii): case management services; and
              30-3-38(5)(a)(iii): administrative services.
          30-3-38(5)(b): An entity who contracts with the Department of Health and Human Services under Subsection a[Ref: 30-3-38(5)(a)]
              30-3-38(5)(b)(i): be qualified to provide one or more of the services listed in Subsection a[Ref: 30-3-38(5)(a)]
              30-3-38(5)(b)(ii): agree to follow billing guidelines established by the Department of Health and Human Services and this section.
      30-3-38(6): 
          30-3-38(6)(a): Except as provided in Subsection b[Ref: 30-3-38(6)(b)]
              30-3-38(6)(a)(i): reduced to a sum certain;
              30-3-38(6)(a)(ii): divided equally between the parents; and
              30-3-38(6)(a)(iii): charged against each parent taking into account the ability of that parent to pay under billing guidelines adopted in accordance with this section.
          30-3-38(6)(b): A judge may order a parent to pay an amount in excess of that provided for in Subsection a[Ref: 30-3-38(6)(a)]
              30-3-38(6)(b)(i): failed to participate in good faith in mediation or services to facilitate parent-time; or
              30-3-38(6)(b)(ii): made an unfounded assertion or claim of physical or sexual abuse of a child.
          30-3-38(6)(c): 
              30-3-38(6)(c)(i): The cost of mediation and services to facilitate parent-time may be charged to parents at periodic intervals.
              30-3-38(6)(c)(ii): Mediation and services to facilitate parent-time may only be terminated on the ground of nonpayment if both parents are delinquent.
      30-3-38(7): 
          30-3-38(7)(a): The Judicial Council may make rules to implement and administer the provisions of this program related to mediation.
          30-3-38(7)(b): The Department of Health and Human Services may make rules to implement and administer the provisions of this program related to services to facilitate parent-time.
      30-3-38(8): 
          30-3-38(8)(a): The Administrative Office of the Courts shall adopt outcome measures to evaluate the effectiveness of the mediation component of this program.  Progress reports shall be provided to the Judiciary Interim Committee as requested by the committee.
          30-3-38(8)(b): The Department of Health and Human Services shall adopt outcome measures to evaluate the effectiveness of the services component of this program.  Progress reports shall be provided to the Judiciary Interim Committee as requested by the committee.
          30-3-38(8)(c): The Administrative Office of the Courts and the Department of Health and Human Services may adopt joint outcome measures and file joint reports to satisfy the requirements of Subsections a[Ref: 30-3-38(7)(a)] b[Ref: 30-3-38(7)(b)]
      30-3-38(9): The Department of Health and Human Services shall, by following the procedures and requirements of 63J-5[Ref: 63J-5]
    Section: 30-3-39 - Mediation program.
      Enacted: Amended by Chapter by Chapter 3, 2008GS
      30-3-39(1): There is established a mandatory domestic mediation program to help reduce the time and tensions associated with obtaining a divorce.
      30-3-39(2): If, after the filing of an answer to a complaint of divorce, there are any remaining contested issues, the parties shall participate in good faith in at least one session of mediation.  This requirement does not preclude the entry of pretrial orders before mediation takes place.
      30-3-39(3): The parties shall use a mediator qualified to mediate domestic disputes under criteria established by the Judicial Council in accordance with Section 78B-6-205[Ref: 78B-6-205]
      30-3-39(4): Unless otherwise ordered by the court or the parties agree upon a different payment arrangement, the cost of mediation shall be divided equally between the parties.
      30-3-39(5): The director of dispute resolution programs for the courts, the court, or the mediator may excuse either party from the requirement to mediate for good cause.
      30-3-39(6): Mediation shall be conducted in accordance with the Utah Rules of Court-Annexed Alternative Dispute Resolution.
  Chapter: 30-4 - Separate Maintenance
    Section: 30-4-1 - Action by spouse -- Grounds.
      Enacted: Amended by Chapter by Chapter 137, 1993GS
      30-4-1(1): deserts a spouse without good and sufficient cause;
      30-4-1(2): being of sufficient ability to provide support, neglects or refuses to properly provide for and suitably maintain that spouse;
      30-4-1(3): having property within this state and the spouse being a resident of this state, so deserts or neglects or refuses to provide such support; or
      30-4-1(4): where a married person without that person's fault lives separate and apart from that spouse, the district court shall, on the filing of a complaint, allot, assign, set apart and decree as alimony the use of the real and personal estate or earnings of the deserting spouse as the court may determine appropriate. During the pendency of the action, the court may require the deserting spouse to pay a sum as provided in Section 30-3-3[Ref: 30-3-3]
    Section: 30-4-2 - Procedure -- Venue.
      Enacted: Amended by Chapter by Chapter 122, 1977GS
    Section: 30-4-3 - Custody and maintenance of children -- Property and debt division -- Support payments.
      Enacted: Amended by Chapter by Chapter 257, 1991GS
      30-4-3(1): In all actions brought under this chapter the court may by order or decree:
          30-4-3(1)(a): provide for the care, custody, and maintenance of the minor children of the parties and may determine with which of the parties the children or any of them shall remain;
          30-4-3(1)(b): 
              30-4-3(1)(b)(i): provide for support of either spouse and the support of the minor children remaining with that spouse;
              30-4-3(1)(b)(ii): provide how and when support payments shall be made; and
              30-4-3(1)(b)(iii): provide that either spouse have a lien upon the property of the other to secure payment of the support or maintenance obligation;
          30-4-3(1)(c): award to either spouse the possession of any real or personal property of the other spouse or acquired by the spouses during the marriage; or
          30-4-3(1)(d): pursuant to Section 15-4-6.5[Ref: 15-4-6.5]
              30-4-3(1)(d)(i): specify which party is responsible for the payment of joint debts, obligations, or liabilities contracted or incurred by the parties during the marriage;
              30-4-3(1)(d)(ii): require the parties to notify respective creditors or obligees regarding the court's division of debts, obligations, and liabilities and regarding the parties' separate, current addresses; and
              30-4-3(1)(d)(iii): provide for the enforcement of these orders.
      30-4-3(2): The orders and decrees under this section may be enforced by sale of any property of the spouse or by contempt proceedings or otherwise as may be necessary.
      30-4-3(3): The court may change the support or maintenance of a party from time to time according to circumstances, and may terminate altogether any obligation upon satisfactory proof of voluntary and permanent reconciliation.   An order or decree of support or maintenance shall in every case be valid only during the joint lives of the husband and wife.
