  Chapter: 30-5 - Grandparents
    Section: 30-5-1 - Definitions.
      Enacted: Amended by Chapter by Chapter 48, 2020GS
      30-5-1(1): "District court" means the district court with proper jurisdiction over the grandchild.
      30-5-1(2): "Grandchild" means the child with respect to whom a grandparent is seeking visitation rights under this chapter.
      30-5-1(3): "Grandparent" means an individual whose child, either by blood, marriage, or adoption, is the parent of the grandchild.
    Section: 30-5-2 - Visitation rights of grandparents.
      Enacted: Amended by Chapter by Chapter 335, 2022GS
      30-5-2(1): In accordance with the provisions and requirements of this section:
          30-5-2(1)(a): a grandparent has standing to bring an action requesting visitation in district court by petition; and
          30-5-2(1)(b): a grandparent may file a petition for visitation rights in the juvenile court or district court where a divorce proceeding or other proceeding involving custody and visitation issues is pending.
      30-5-2(2): 
          30-5-2(2)(a): In accordance with Section 80-2a-201[Ref: 80-2a-201]
          30-5-2(2)(b): A court shall presume that a parent's decision in regard to grandparent visitation is in the best interest of the parent's child.
      30-5-2(3): A court may find the presumption in Subsection b[Ref: 30-5-2(2)(b)]
          30-5-2(3)(a): the grandparent has filled the role of custodian or caregiver to the grandchild that:
              30-5-2(3)(a)(i): is in a manner akin to a parent; and
              30-5-2(3)(a)(ii): the loss of the relationship between the grandparent and the grandchild would cause substantial harm to the grandchild; or
          30-5-2(3)(b): both parents are unfit or incompetent in a manner that causes potential harm to the grandchild.
      30-5-2(4): 
          30-5-2(4)(a): If the court finds the presumption in Subsection b[Ref: 30-5-2(2)(b)]
          30-5-2(4)(b): If the court considers whether grandparent visitation is in the best interest of the child, the court shall take into account the totality of the circumstances, including:
              30-5-2(4)(b)(i): the reasonableness of the parent's decision to deny grandparent visitation;
              30-5-2(4)(b)(ii): the age of the grandchild;
              30-5-2(4)(b)(iii): the death or unavailability of a parent; and
              30-5-2(4)(b)(iv): if the grandchild is 14 years old or older, the grandchild's desires regarding visitation after the court inquires of the grandchild.
      30-5-2(5): If the court finds the presumption in Subsection b[Ref: 30-5-2(2)(b)]
      30-5-2(6): The adoption of a grandchild by the grandchild's stepparent does not diminish or alter visitation rights previously ordered under this section.
      30-5-2(7): On the petition of a grandparent or the legal custodian of a grandchild the court may, after a hearing, modify an order regarding grandparent visitation if:
          30-5-2(7)(a): the circumstances of the grandchild, the grandparent, or the custodian have materially and substantially changed since the entry of the order to be modified, or the order has become unworkable or inappropriate under existing circumstances; and
          30-5-2(7)(b): the court determines that a modification is appropriate based upon the factors set forth in Subsections 3[Ref: 30-5-2(3)] 4[Ref: 30-5-2(4)]
      30-5-2(8): A grandparent may petition the court to remedy a parent's wrongful noncompliance with a visitation order.
